    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-26T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-26T12:00:00-05:00" n="232"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d232">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/960</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EMF1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Egan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-26T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 26, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 27, 7.55 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1627. The German proposal to treat with Russia for a separate peace, announced in
                    to-day’s telegrams, provided the latter first withdraw one hundred kilometers
                    from the present front, is clearly an attempt to cause the dissolution of what
                    remains of the Russian Army, to come into easy possession of the war material
                    and foodstuffs within that zone and with their paid agent <persName
                        corresp="#p_LNVU1">Lenin</persName> in control to dictate terms insuring
                    Teutonic commercial and political ascendancy in Russia for generations to come.
                    Prussia victorious is certain to make heavy demands. German press views on the
                    subject will be cabled to-morrow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
